Step 1: Create an account with Kaggle

Create Kaggle Account and download API key

Below is example of steps to get the API username and key. Each student will have their own username and key.

  1. Open account settings.
  2. Scroll down to API and click Create New API Token.
  3. Open up kaggle.json and use the username and key.

Step 2: Download the Kaggle dataset using the kaggle python library

Open up Sagemaker Studio and use starter template

  1. Notebook should be using a ml.t3.medium instance (2 vCPU + 4 GiB)
  2. Notebook should be using kernal: Python 3 (MXNet 1.8 Python 3.7 CPU Optimized)

# I've imported my kaggle.json file and move it in the right directory
import os

# Define the correct path for SageMaker Studio user
kaggle_dir = os.path.expanduser("~/.kaggle")
kaggle_path = os.path.join(kaggle_dir, "kaggle.json")

# Create the .kaggle directory
os.makedirs(kaggle_dir, exist_ok=True)

# If you have your kaggle.json ready to upload, upload it via the Jupyter file upload button
# and move it to the right location:
import shutil
shutil.move("kaggle.json", kaggle_path)  # This assumes you uploaded 'kaggle.json' to the notebook directory

# Set proper file permissions
os.chmod(kaggle_path, 0o600)

Step 3: Train a model using AutoGluons Tabular Prediction

Requirements:

  • We are predicting count, so it is the label we are setting.
  • Ignore casual and registered columns as they are also not present in the test dataset.
  • Use the root_mean_squared_error as the metric to use for evaluation.
  • Set a time limit of 10 minutes (600 seconds).
  • Use the preset best_quality to focus on creating the best model.
In[11]:
train_data = train.drop(columns=["casual", "registered"])
predictor = TabularPredictor(
    label="count",
    eval_metric="root_mean_squared_error"
).fit(
    train_data,
    time_limit=600,
    presets="best_quality"
)

Step 4: Exploratory Data Analysis and Creating an additional feature

  • Any additional feature will do, but a great suggestion would be to separate out the datetime into hour, day, or month parts.
In[22]:
# Create a histogram of all features to show the distribution of each one relative to the data. This is part of the exploritory data analysis
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Plot histogram of all numerical features
train.hist(figsize=(14, 10), bins=30)
plt.suptitle("Feature Distributions in Train Dataset", fontsize=16)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.93)
plt.show()
In[23]:
# create a new feature
train["hour"] = train["datetime"].dt.hour
train["day"] = train["datetime"].dt.dayofweek  # 0 = Monday, 6 = Sunday
train["month"] = train["datetime"].dt.month

# Apply the same transformations to the test set
test["hour"] = test["datetime"].dt.hour
test["day"] = test["datetime"].dt.dayofweek
test["month"] = test["datetime"].dt.month

Make category types for these so models know they are not just numbers

  • AutoGluon originally sees these as ints, but in reality they are int representations of a category.
  • Setting the dtype to category will classify these as categories in AutoGluon.
In[]:
train["season"] = train["season"].astype("category")
train["weather"] = train["weather"].astype("category")

test["season"] = test["season"].astype("category")
test["weather"] = test["weather"].astype("category")

Step 6: Hyper parameter optimization

  • There are many options for hyper parameter optimization.
  • Options are to change the AutoGluon higher level parameters or the individual model hyperparameters.
  • The hyperparameters of the models themselves that are in AutoGluon. Those need the hyperparameter and hyperparameter_tune_kwargs arguments.
In[49]:
from autogluon.common import space as ag_space  


# Define search-spaces for each model type


nn_options = {                     
    "num_epochs": 30,
    "learning_rate": ag_space.Real(1e-4, 1e-2, log=True, default=5e-4),
    "activation":   ag_space.Categorical("relu", "softrelu", "tanh"),
    "dropout_prob": ag_space.Real(0.0, 0.5, default=0.1),
}

gbm_options = {                    # LightGBM search-space
    "num_boost_round": 100,
    "num_leaves":     ag_space.Int(26, 66, default=36),
}

rf_options = {                     # Random-Forest search-space
    "n_estimators":    ag_space.Int(300, 800, default=500),
    "max_depth":       ag_space.Int(8, 25,   default=15),
    "min_samples_leaf":ag_space.Int(1, 10,   default=2),
    "max_features":    ag_space.Real(0.3, 1.0, default=0.7),
}

hyperparameters = {
    "GBM"      : gbm_options,   # LightGBM
    "NN_TORCH" : nn_options,    # Torch neural net
    "RF"       : rf_options,    # Random-Forest
}

# HPO scheduler / searcher configuration

hpo_kwargs = {
    "num_trials": 5,        
    "scheduler" : "local",  
    "searcher"  : "auto",   # AutoGluon picks random or bayesopt
}



# Train with hyper-parameter tuning

predictor_new_hpo = TabularPredictor(
    label="count",
    eval_metric="root_mean_squared_error"
).fit(
    train_data=train_data_new,          
    time_limit=600,
    hyperparameters=hyperparameters,         
    hyperparameter_tune_kwargs=hpo_kwargs,   
)

In[62]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
import numpy as np
def preprocess_data(train, test):
    # Convert to datetime if not already done
    train['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(train['datetime'])
    test['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(test['datetime'])
    
    # --- Feature Engineering ---
    for df in [train, test]:
        # Time-based features
        df['hour'] = df['datetime'].dt.hour
        df['day'] = df['datetime'].dt.day
        df['month'] = df['datetime'].dt.month
        df['year'] = df['datetime'].dt.year
        df['weekday'] = df['datetime'].dt.weekday  # Monday=0, Sunday=6
        
        # Derived features
        df['weekend'] = df['weekday'].isin([5, 6]).astype(int)
        df['rush_hour'] = df['hour'].isin([7, 8, 17, 18]).astype(int)
        df['is_daytime'] = df['hour'].between(6, 20).astype(int)
        
        # Cyclical encoding 
        df['season_sin'] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * df['season'] / 4)
        df['season_cos'] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * df['season'] / 4)
        
    
    
    # One-hot encode weather (3 categories after grouping)
    train = pd.get_dummies(train, columns=['weather'], prefix='weather')
    test = pd.get_dummies(test, columns=['weather'], prefix='weather')
    
    # Ensure test has all weather columns (
    missing_cols = set(train.columns) - set(test.columns)
    for col in missing_cols:
        if 'weather_' in col:
            test[col] = 0
    
    # --- Final Cleanup ---
    # Drop original datetime and redundant columns
    cols_to_drop = ['season','casual', 'registered']  # season is now encoded cyclically
    train = train.drop(columns=cols_to_drop, errors='ignore')
    test = test.drop(columns=cols_to_drop, errors='ignore')
    
    # Align columns 
    test = test[train.columns.drop('count', errors='ignore')]
    
    return train, test


train_processed, test_processed = preprocess_data(train.copy(), test.copy())

# 2)  AUTOMATIC OUTLIER REMOVAL VIA IQR

def drop_iqr_outliers(df: pd.DataFrame, column: str, iqr_multiplier: float = 1.5):
    """
    Remove rows whose <column> lies outside [Q1-k*IQR, Q3+k*IQR].
    Returns the cleaned DataFrame and the mask of kept rows.
    """
    q1  = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    q3  = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower = q1 - iqr_multiplier * iqr
    upper = q3 + iqr_multiplier * iqr
    mask  = df[column].between(lower, upper)
    return df.loc[mask], mask

#  drop outliers on the target 'count'
train, kept_mask = drop_iqr_outliers(train, "count")

print(f"Rows before: {len(train):,}    after cleaning: {len(train_clean):,}")

from autogluon.common import space as ag_space  


# Define search-spaces for each model type


nn_options = {                     
    "num_epochs": 30,
    "learning_rate": ag_space.Real(1e-4, 1e-2, log=True, default=5e-4),
    "activation":   ag_space.Categorical("relu", "softrelu", "tanh"),
    "dropout_prob": ag_space.Real(0.0, 0.5, default=0.1),
}

gbm_options = {                    # LightGBM search-space
    "num_boost_round": 100,
    "num_leaves":     ag_space.Int(26, 66, default=36),
}

rf_options = {                     # Random-Forest search-space
    "n_estimators":    ag_space.Int(300, 800, default=500),
    "max_depth":       ag_space.Int(8, 25,   default=15),
    "min_samples_leaf":ag_space.Int(1, 10,   default=2),
    "max_features":    ag_space.Real(0.3, 1.0, default=0.7),
}

hyperparameters = {
    "GBM"      : gbm_options,   # LightGBM
    "NN_TORCH" : nn_options,    # Torch neural net
    "RF"       : rf_options,    # Random-Forest
}

# HPO scheduler / searcher configuration

hpo_kwargs = {
    "num_trials": 5,        
    "scheduler" : "local",  
    "searcher"  : "auto",   # AutoGluon picks random or bayesopt
}



# Train with hyper-parameter tuning

predictor = TabularPredictor(

    eval_metric="root_mean_squared_error"
).fit(
    train_data=train,          
    time_limit=1200,
    hyperparameters=hyperparameters,         
    hyperparameter_tune_kwargs=hpo_kwargs,   
    verbosity=3,
)

from autogluon.tabular import TabularPredictor
import pandas as pd


models_to_test = {
    'XGBoost': 'XGB',
    'Random Forest': 'RF',
    'Neural Network': 'NN_TORCH',
    'KNN': 'KNN',
}

results = {}
predictors = {} 
# Loop through each model
for model_name, model_code in models_to_test.items():
    print(f"\n=== Testing {model_name} ===")
    
    # Train model using RMSE and best_quality
    predictor = TabularPredictor(
        label='count',
        eval_metric='root_mean_squared_error',
        verbosity=1
    ).fit(
        train_data=train,
        time_limit=300,  
        hyperparameters={model_code: {}},
        presets='medium_quality'
    )
    
    # Get leaderboard and actual RMSE (note: negate score_val to get true RMSE)
    leaderboard = predictor.leaderboard(silent=True)
    score_val = leaderboard.loc[0, 'score_val']
    fit_time = leaderboard.loc[0, 'fit_time']
    
    results[model_name] = {
        'RMSE': -score_val,  # Convert to positive RMSE
        'Fit Time (s)': fit_time
    }
    print(f"{model_name} | Val RMSE: {-score_val:.4f}")
    predictors[model_name] = predictor
# Create results table
results_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(results, orient='index')
results_df = results_df.sort_values('RMSE')
print("\n=== Final RMSE Comparison ===")
print(results_df)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# --- Performance Comparison ---
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
results_df['RMSE'].plot.barh(color='skyblue')
plt.title('Algorithm Performance Comparison (Lower RMSE is Better)')
plt.xlabel('Validation RMSE')
plt.grid(axis='x', linestyle='--')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Optional: puts best model on top
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# --- Speed vs Accuracy ---
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.scatter(
    results_df['RMSE'], 
    results_df['Fit Time (s)'],
    s=200, alpha=0.6
)
for model in results_df.index:
    plt.text(
        x=results_df.loc[model, 'RMSE'],
        y=results_df.loc[model, 'Fit Time (s)'],
        s=model,
        ha='center',
        va='bottom',
        fontsize=9
    )
plt.title('Accuracy vs Training Time')
plt.xlabel('RMSE (Lower is Better)')
plt.ylabel('Training Time (seconds)')
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
